      <h1 class="text-4xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-gray-900">How to Find Legitimate Remote Jobs: Platforms, Scams, and What Actually Works</h1>
      <p class="mt-4 text-lg leading-8 text-gray-600">
        The remote job market is full of opportunity — and scams. Here is how to find real positions, avoid the most common traps, and actually get hired.
      </p>

      <div class="mt-10 prose prose-lg prose-gray max-w-none">

        <p>Remote job scams are rampant. The FBI's Internet Crime Complaint Center reported that employment scams increased by over 200% between 2020 and 2025. These are not subtle — "earn $500/day stuffing envelopes" obvious scams. They are sophisticated operations with fake LinkedIn profiles, realistic-looking company websites, and multi-stage "interviews" conducted entirely over text chat.</p>

        <p>I have helped several friends navigate the remote job search over the past few years. Some of them found great roles. One almost fell for a check-cashing scam that would have cost her $3,000. The difference between those outcomes was knowing which platforms to trust and which red flags to recognize.</p>

        <h2>The platforms that actually work</h2>

        <h3>LinkedIn — Still the biggest pool</h3>

        <p>LinkedIn has more remote job listings than any other platform, across every industry. The "Remote" location filter works, though some companies list positions as "Remote" when they mean "Remote until we change our mind," so read the description carefully. Set up job alerts for your target role with the remote filter applied — the early applicants get the most attention.</p>

        <p>The Easy Apply button is convenient, but an application submitted in 15 seconds looks like it. Take the extra five minutes to tailor your resume and write a brief note. It genuinely makes a difference.</p>

        <h3>FlexJobs — The safest option</h3>

        <p>FlexJobs employs actual humans who manually screen every listing before it goes live. You will never find a scam on FlexJobs. The tradeoff: it costs $2.95 per week (or about $72/year) to apply to jobs. For many job seekers, the time saved not sorting through fake listings is worth the cost. FlexJobs also covers a broader range of industries than most remote-only boards — healthcare, education, customer support, and non-tech roles are well-represented.</p>

        <h3>We Work Remotely — Best for tech and design</h3>

        <p>One of the oldest remote-only job boards. Every listing is guaranteed remote. Employers pay $299 to post, which naturally filters for companies that are serious about hiring. The listings skew heavily toward software development, design, and marketing roles. If you are in tech, this should be one of your daily checks. If you are not, the pickings are slimmer.</p>

        <h3>Wellfound (AngelList) — Best for startup roles</h3>

        <p>Wellfound is the go-to for startup and tech company jobs. The key differentiator: salary and equity information is transparent — you can see exactly what the compensation range is before you apply. Direct communication with founders and hiring managers rather than going through HR. The downside: it is almost entirely tech and startup roles, and most companies are US-based.</p>

        <h3>Upwork — For freelancers, not full-time seekers</h3>

        <p>Upwork is the largest freelance marketplace. It is a good place to build a portfolio and client base, especially when you are starting out. But the platform takes a 10% service fee on your earnings, and competition for projects can be intense, particularly at the entry level. Use Upwork to build experience and references; do not rely on it as your primary source of full-time income.</p>

        <p>For a detailed side-by-side comparison of platforms — with salary ranges, job types, and experience level requirements — use our <a href="/tools/remote-job-finder/">Remote Job Finder</a>.</p>

        <h2>Red flags that scream "scam"</h2>

        <p>These are not subtle signals. If any of these happen, stop engaging immediately:</p>

        <p><strong>They send you a check to buy equipment.</strong> This is the most common remote job scam and it is devastating. Process: the "employer" emails a check for $3,000-5,000, tells you to deposit it and use the money to buy a laptop and software from their "approved vendor." You deposit the check. The bank makes the funds available (as required by law). You send money to the "vendor" — which is actually the scammer. A week later, the check bounces. You are out the money you sent, plus overdraft fees, plus the bank may close your account for depositing a fraudulent check. The "vendor" is gone.</p>

        <p><strong>Do not ever deposit a check from someone you have not met in person, for a job you have not started, for equipment you have not received.</strong> Legitimate companies ship you equipment directly — they do not send you money to buy it yourself.</p>

        <p><strong>Interview conducted entirely over text chat.</strong> No legitimate company interviews candidates exclusively through Telegram, WhatsApp, or text-based chat. Real companies do at least one video or phone call. If your entire "interview" happens via text, it is a scam — even if the person seems professional and the company looks real on Google.</p>

        <p><strong>They ask for money upfront.</strong> No variation of this is legitimate. Not for training. Not for a "starter kit." Not for a background check fee. Not for "processing your application." Real employers pay for these things. You should never pay to get a job. Ever.</p>

        <p><strong>The salary is unrealistically high for the role.</strong> "$80/hour for data entry, no experience required" — I wish this needed explaining. It is a scam. If it sounds too good to be true, it is.</p>

        <p><strong>Poor communication and urgency.</strong> Emails from Gmail addresses rather than company domains. Messages full of typos and awkward grammar. Pressure to "act now" or claims that the position will be filled within 24 hours. Real companies have HR processes. They do not rush candidates through a hiring funnel.</p>

        <p><strong>They ask for sensitive personal information too early.</strong> Social Security number, bank account details, passport scan — these should only be requested after you have accepted a formal written job offer. Never include them in an initial application.</p>

        <h2>Practical tips that actually improve your chances</h2>

        <p>Remote jobs get 2-3 times more applications than equivalent in-office roles, according to data from LinkedIn and Indeed. You need to be fast and good. Set up alerts and apply within 24-48 hours of a posting going live. Tailor your resume to each application — generic applications are easy to spot and almost never get interviews.</p>

        <p>Highlight remote work skills explicitly: self-discipline, written communication, time management, experience with remote tools (Slack, Zoom, Notion, etc.). These matter as much as your technical qualifications for remote roles. Employers have been burned by people who had great credentials but could not function without in-person supervision. Show them you can work independently.</p>

        <p>Set up a professional video call environment before you have an interview scheduled. Good lighting, a clean background, and quality audio are not vanity — they signal competence. When your webcam turns on and you look and sound professional, you have already differentiated yourself from the candidates calling in from their dimly lit kitchen with laptop audio.</p>

